      <hedline>
        <hl1>The Environment, and Our Votes</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Prof Michael W Golay letter, commenting on August 28 editorial on looming environmental problems that seem to have taken back seat in presidential election, says neither Vice Pres Gore nor Gov George W Bush have much to offer on issue</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Your Aug. 28 editorial ''Protecting the Earth'' praises Al Gore for his ''detailed'' and ''muscular'' energy policy statement as opposed to the vacancy of George W. Bush's. In fact, neither has anything to show in this area.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Your Aug. 28 editorial ''Protecting the Earth'' praises Al Gore for his ''detailed'' and ''muscular'' energy policy statement as opposed to the vacancy of George W. Bush's. In fact, neither has anything to show in this area.</p>
        <p>The global-warming response plan of Mr. Gore would save the planet without recourse to nuclear and hydroelectric energy, the only available nonemitting industrial-strength energy technologies. Their omission from his ''policy'' is the surest sign that it is not one.</p>
        <p>MICHAEL W. GOLAY  Cambridge, Mass., Aug. 29, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer is a professor of nuclear engineering at M.I.T.</p>
      </block>
